reut2-010.sgm, ANALYSTS PEG U.S. COTTON SEEDINGS 10.6 MLN ACRES, U.S. cotton farmers are likely toplant about 10.6 mln acres in the coming season, based on anaverage of estimates offered by cotton market analysts gearingup for the U.S. Agriculture Department's 1987 plantingintentions report next Tuesday.    The annual report gives cotton traders their first glimpseof what U.S. production might be in the 1987/88 season, whichbegins August 1.    Trade and commission house forecasts ranged from 10.2 to10.9 mln acres.    On March 18 of last year, the USDA reported that cottonfarmers in 1986 intended to plant 9.71 mln acres.    Four months later, the USDA estimated that 9.67 mln acreshad been planted as of June 1. By January, its estimate of 1986planted acreage nationwide was 10.06 mln.    Analysts said their forecasts for even greater acreage in1987 were spurred in part by belief that this year's gooddemand and firm prices will be repeated next year. Analystssaid those factors make cotton a profitable crop.    With cotton more attractive price-wise

